What is DevOps?  #DevOps is a set of practices, principles, and cultural philosophies that 
                   # bring together software development (Dev) and IT operations (Ops).
                   #The goal is to improve the speed, quality, and reliability of software delivery 
                   #by breaking down silos between developers and system administrators

 Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC)

SDLC is the process of planning, creating, testing, deploying, and maintaining software.
It‚Äôs like the blueprint for building software, just like engineers follow steps when constructing a bridge.

The two most common models are:

Waterfall (traditional)

Agile (modern/iterative)

1Ô∏è‚É£ Waterfall Model
üìù How It Works

Linear and sequential ‚Üí each phase must finish before the next starts.

Looks like a waterfall, flowing down step by step.

üîπ Phases

Requirement Gathering ‚Üí understand what the client wants.

Design ‚Üí plan the architecture.

Implementation (Coding) ‚Üí developers write code.

Testing ‚Üí QA team tests the system. #qat #uat

Deployment ‚Üí deliver to customer.

Maintenance ‚Üí fix bugs, updates.

üîπ Example

Imagine you‚Äôre building software for a bank ATM:

Step 1: Collect requirements ‚Üí ‚ÄúATM must allow withdrawals, deposits, balance checks.‚Äù

Step 2: Design system ‚Üí database schema, UI layout.

Step 3: Code everything.

Step 4: Test after coding is complete.

Step 5: Deploy to ATMs.
üëâ If requirements change later (e.g., ‚Äúadd mobile money transfer‚Äù), it‚Äôs very costly because you must redo design + code.
example: 

NASA uses Waterfall for spacecraft software. Why? Because once launched, you can‚Äôt update software easily ‚Üí everything must be perfect before release.

Agile Model
üìù How It Works

Iterative & incremental ‚Üí software is developed in small cycles (sprints).

Emphasizes flexibility, customer feedback, and continuous improvement.

üîπ Agile Principles

Work is divided into sprints (usually 2‚Äì4 weeks).

Each sprint delivers a working product increment.

Feedback is given at the end of each sprint ‚Üí changes are adapted quickly.

üîπ Example

Imagine you‚Äôre building a food delivery app:

Sprint 1: Build login + signup.

Sprint 2: Add restaurant browsing.

Sprint 3: Add cart + order placement.

Sprint 4: Add payments.
üëâ The customer sees progress after each sprint and can request changes early (e.g., ‚Äúadd PayPal instead of only credit card‚Äù).

Waterfall vs Agile (Quick Comparison)
Aspect	                 Waterfall üèûÔ∏è	                                    Agile üöÄ
Process	          Sequential (step by step)	                      Iterative (small cycles/sprints)
Flexibility       Low ‚Üí hard to change later	                High ‚Üí easy to adapt to new needs
Testing	           After coding is complete	                      Continuous, in every sprint
Delivery	      Single release at the end	Frequent                  releases (every 2‚Äì4 weeks)
Example Use Case	   NASA spacecraft software                   	Food delivery app, Spotify, e-commerce

